\boxed{Marcel Proust}

Proust famously declared in *À la recherche du temps perdu* (1913–1927) that "the only true voyage of discovery... would be not to visit strange lands but to possess other eyes," but his insistence on *volonté de réalité*—the rigorous pursuit of truth in memory and perception—was seen by some critics (like Jean-Paul Sartre) as a "narcotic" for its hypnotic, almost addictive demand for historical and psychological precision. The phrase about writing history "as what actually happened" aligns with his method of reconstructing the past through subjective experience.
